'''Brandon Marshall''' (born March 23, 1984), nicknamed "The Beast,"<ref>Buettner, Matthew J. [http://cbs4denver.com/broncos/broncos.marshall.suspension.2.808046.html Marshall Wants To Catch 140 Passes This Year]. CBS4Denver.com. September 1, 2008. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.bmarshall15.com/ Brandon Marshall Official Website]. BMarshall15.com. Accessed December 10, 2009.</ref><ref>Watkins, David.[http://www.kare11.com/blog/watkins_article.aspx?storyid=819480 NFL Wide Receiver camp at the U]. KARE 11. July, 2009. Accessed December 10, 2009.</ref><ref>Berardino, Mike. [http://blogs.sun-sentinel.com/sports_football_dolphins/2009/06/miami-dolphins-greg-ellis-and-brandon-marshall.html Miami Dolphins: Greg Ellis and Brandon Marshall]. SunSentinel.com. June 16, 2009. Accessed December 10, 2009.</ref> is an [[American football]] [[wide receiver]] for the [[Denver Broncos]] of the [[National Football League]]. He was selected by the Broncos out of the [[UCF Knights football|University of Central Florida]], with the 119th overall pick in the fourth round of the [[2006 NFL Draft]].<ref name=broncossitebio>[http://www.denverbroncos.com/page.php?id=498&contentID=5909 Brandon Marshall Biography]. DenverBroncos.com. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref>

Marshall is known for his ability to break and dodge [[Tackle (football move)|tackles]].<ref name=fearfactors>Seifert, Kevin. [http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?page=hotread7/seifert Nightmare scenarios: Whom (and what) NFL players fear]. ESPN.com. October 30, 2008. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref>  He led all NFL wide receivers in yards after first contact for the [[2007 NFL season]].<ref name=broncossitebio />  Regarding Marshall's breakaway ability, [[Kansas City Chiefs]] [[cornerback]] [[Brandon Flowers (American football)|Brandon Flowers]] said, "Brandon Marshall is a [[defensive lineman]] playing wide receiver.  He wants to inflict punishment on you. He wants you to try to tackle him so he can shove you off of him and get more yards."<ref name=fearfactors />  [[Oakland Raiders]] cornerback [[Nnamdi Asomugha]] said Marshall is "the toughest guy to bring down, one-on-one."<ref>Klis, Mike. [http://www.denverpost.com/sports/ci_11640776 Marshall stands tall in Pro Bowl crowd]. ''The Denver Post''. February 6, 2009. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref>

On December 13, 2009, Marshall set an NFL record for [[Reception (American football)|receptions]] in a game with 21.<ref name=21catches>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4739282 Marshall surpasses T.O.'s 20-catch mark]. ESPN.com. December 13, 2009. Accessed December 13, 2009.</ref> He is also only one of five players in NFL history to catch at least 100 passes in three consecutive seasons.<ref name=threeseasons>Eisendrath, Zach. [http://www.denverbroncos.com/page.php?id=334&storyID=9712 The Morning After:  Week 16]. DenverBroncos.com. December 28, 2009. Accessed December 29, 2009.</ref>

==Early life==
Marshall was born in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=broncossitebio />  He later lived in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], then moved to [[Florida]], where he played high school football at [[Lake Howell High School]].<ref>Schwab, Frank. [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4191/is_/ai_n16804725 The making of an NFL-caliber receiver]. ''The Gazette''. October 1, 2006. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref>  Marshall played both offense and defense, as he earned All-State honors and was named Seminole County Utility Player of the Year.  He also lettered in [[basketball]] and [[track and field athletics|track]] three times.  As a senior, Marshall won the Class 3A state [[triple jump]] championship, landing a jump of 48-feet, six-and-three-quarter inches.<ref name=broncossitebio />

==College career==
Marshall played a total of 44 games (21 starts) at wide receiver for the [[UCF Knights football|University of Central Florida]], collecting 112 receptions, 1,674 receiving yards and 13 touchdowns in his collegiate career.<ref name=broncossitebio /> His best season came in 2005 as a senior. He played in 13 games and had career highs in receptions (74), receiving yards (1,195) and touchdowns (11). Marshall's best career game came in the [[2005 Hawaii Bowl]], where he had 11 catches for 210 yards and three touchdowns.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=253582116 Missed extra point in OT hands Nevada Hawaii Bowl title]. Associated Press. December 24, 2005. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref>  He was named [[Most Valuable Player|MVP]] of the game.  For his efforts during the 2005 season, Marshall was selected to the All-[[Conference USA|C-USA]] second team.<ref name=broncossitebio />

Marshall also started at [[Safety (defensive back)|safety]] for seven games during the 2004 season due to injuries in UCF's secondary. He made his first collegiate start at safety on October 4, 2004, against [[Buffalo Bulls football|Buffalo]].<ref name=ucfsitebio>[http://ucfathletics.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/marshall_brandon00.html Player Bio: Brandon Marshall]. UCFAthletics.com. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref> He recorded four tackles, including a half of a sack. Marshall led his entire team in tackles (51) during the 2004 season.<ref name=ucfsitebio /> He also had an interception and a forced fumble.

==Professional career==
===2006 NFL Draft===
The [[Denver Broncos]] selected Marshall with the 119th overall selection in the fourth round of the [[2006 NFL Draft]].<ref name=broncossitebio />

