==Personal==
Marshall enjoys restoring [[vintage car|vintage automobiles]].<ref name=broncossitebio />  He is a member of the [[Kappa Alpha Psi]] fraternity and does charity work with them.  He is involved in an ongoing effort to rebuild Larimer Park in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=broncossitebio />

===Legal trouble===
According to Orlando-[[Orange County, Florida|Orange County]] public records (case 48-2004-MM-012392-O), on [[Halloween]] 2004, while a student at UCF, Marshall was arrested in Orlando on charges of assault on a law enforcement officer, refusal to obey, disorderly conduct and resisting an officer.<ref>[http://www.myorangeclerk.com/ Orange County Clerk of Courts]. MyOrangeClerk.com. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref>

On January 1, 2007, Marshall was present at "The Shelter," a nightclub in [[Denver, Colorado|Denver]], [[Colorado]], along with teammates [[Javon Walker]] and [[Darrent Williams]]. The trio was attending a birthday party held for and by [[Denver Nuggets]] [[Power forward (basketball)|forward]] [[Kenyon Martin]]. As the players were leaving the club in a limousine, Williams was fatally shot in the neck after an unknown assailant opened fire on the vehicle. Willie Clark was later charged with the murder.<ref>Cardona, Felisa. [http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_11944690 High bail set for 3 murder suspects] ''The Denver Post''. March 19, 2009. Accessed April 8th, 2009</ref> Walker has stated in interviews that the shooter was likely a nightclub patron whose motive was retaliation after being involved in an altercation with Marshall's cousin earlier that night.<ref>[http://www.hbo.com/realsports/stories/2007/episode.125.s3.html Real Sports With Bryant Gumbel: Episode 125]. HBO.com. August 14, 2007. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref>

On March 26, 2007, Marshall was arrested in the [[Highlands Ranch, Colorado|Highlands Ranch]] suburb of Denver on suspicion of [[domestic violence]] after his girlfriend reported that following a domestic dispute, Marshall prevented a taxi she was in from leaving his house.<ref>Jones, Lindsay H. [http://www.denverpost.com/broncos/ci_9731406 Violent tendency, no penalty]. ''The Denver Post''. June 29, 2008. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref>  Charges from the incident were later dismissed on May 25, 2007, after Marshall completed anger management counseling.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2882758 False-imprisonment charge dropped against Broncos' Marshall]. Associated Press. May 25, 2007. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref>

In the early morning of October 22, 2007, Marshall was arrested in the [[Denver-Aurora metropolitan area]] at the intersection of 14th and Blake St. for [[driving under the influence]] of alcohol.<ref>Moreno, Ivan. [http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/local/article/0,1299,DRMN_15_5728658,00.html Brandon Marshall charged with DUI]. ''The Rocky Mountain News''. October 23, 2007. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref> A [[trial (law)|trial]] was scheduled for September 16, but Marshall instead agreed to a [[plea bargain]] four days earlier; he pleaded guilty to a reduced charge of driving while ability impaired.<ref name="marshalldwai">Poppen, Julie. [http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/sep/12/brandon-marshall-pleads-guilty-lesser-charge/?partner=RSS Bronco pleads guilty to DWAI]. ''The Rocky Mountain News''. September 12, 2008. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref>  He was sentenced to one-year [[probation]] and 24 hours of [[community service]]. 

On June 12, 2008, Marshall was ticketed for an illegal lane change, then found to be without his license and proof of insurance.<ref>[http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_9817294 Another traffic ticket for Brandon Marshall]. ''The Denver Post''. July 8, 2008. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref>  The case was eventually dropped as part of a plea bargain for the October 22, 2007 driving incident involving alcohol.<ref name="marshalldwai" />

According to an article published in the ''[[Rocky Mountain News]]'' on July 28, 2008, [[Douglas County, Colorado|Douglas County]] deputies fielded "about 11" calls to Marshall's home since January 2006.  The article stated that one call resulted in Marshall being arrested (the March 26, 2007 domestic dispute), and some did not involve him at all.<ref>Ensslin, John C. [http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/jul/28/deputies-had-more-10-calls-brandon-marshalls-home/ Deputies had more than 10 calls to Brandon Marshall's home]. ''The Rocky Mountain News''. July 28, 2008. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref>

A September 17, 2008 article on CompleteColorado.com stated that the solicitor's office in [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] filed [[misdemeanor]] [[battery (crime)|battery]] charges on September 10 for an alleged incident on March 4, 2008, in [[Atlanta]], Georgia. Marshall was booked on March 6, then released the next day after posting a $1,000 cash bond.<ref>Jones, Lindsay H. [http://www.denverpost.com/broncos/ci_9686832 On-field talent, off-field trouble]. ''The Rocky Mountain News''. June 25, 2008. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref>  The case was assigned to Judge John Mather in Georgia [[state court]].<ref>[http://www.completecolorado.com/Marshall4.html Criminal Charges Filed Against Marshall In Atlanta]. CompleteColorado.com. September 17, 2008. Accessed February 28, 2009.</ref>  On August 14, 2009, a jury in Atlanta found Marshall not guilty.<ref>Brumback, Kate. [http://cbs4denver.com/local/brandon.marshall.atlanta.2.1129105.html Broncos' Brandon Marshall Found Not Guilty]. Associated Press. August 14, 2009. Accessed August 28, 2009.</ref>

On March 1, 2009, Marshall was arrested in Atlanta for disorderly conduct after allegedly being involved in a fight with his fiancee, Michi Nogami-Campbell.  Marshall was released on a $300 bond.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3944945 Marshall arrested for disorderly conduct]. ESPN.com. March 1, 2009. Accessed March 2, 2009.</ref> The charges were dropped the following day.<ref>Klis, Mike. [http://www.denverpost.com/breakingnews/ci_11818361 Marshall charges dismissed]. ''The Denver Post''. March 2, 2009. Accessed March 2, 2009.</ref>

==Accomplishments==
===Awards and honors===
*2&times; [[Pro Bowl]] selection ([[2009 Pro Bowl|2008]], [[2010 Pro Bowl|2009]])
*2&times; [[American Football Conference|AFC]] Offensive Player of the Week - Week 2 (2008), Week 14 (2009)
*[[Thanksgiving Classic#Game MVPs|Pudding Pie Award]] (2009)
*[[2005 Hawaii Bowl]] [[Most Valuable Player|MVP]]
*Second-team All-[[Conference USA|C-USA]] (2005)

===Records and milestones===
*Most catches in an NFL game (21).<ref name=21catches />
*Third-most catches in an NFL game (18).<ref name=2008week2 />
*Most receptions spanning five games in NFL history (55).<ref name=broncossitebio />
*Only player in NFL history to have at least 10 receptions in four out of five games.<ref name=broncossitebio /><ref name=nflmediaweek3 />
*First player since 1960 to record eight career games of at least 10 receptions in his first four seasons.<ref name=2009week14 />
*One of only five players in NFL history (first Broncos player) to catch at least 100 passes in three straight seasons.<ref name=threeseasons />
*Ninth player in NFL history (second Broncos player) to have at least 100 catches in back-to-back seasons (2007 and 2008).<ref name=dpbests />
*Caught 102 passes in 2007 (second-career NFL season), becoming only the third second-year player in NFL history to have at least 100 receptions in a season.<ref name=2007broncosvikingsgame />

